"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707722","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-08","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given by my hon. Friend the Minister of state for International trade (Greg Hands) on the 2 March to rt. hon. Member for Glasgow North UIN 65736.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier","66457","2017-03-08T17:54:03.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707722/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707722/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707722/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-03","Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether he has had discussions with the Leader of the House to ensure that the 21-day ratification period for the Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement takes place during a time in the parliamentary calendar which contains at least one Opposition Day.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","66429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707723","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-03-13","<p>Stakeholder engagement is at the core of our plans to build a national consensus around our negotiating position; we are listening and talking to as many organisations, companies and institutions as we can. The Secretary of State and Junior Ministers will aim to visit every sector and every region of the UK.<br><br>I have recently heard from a range of stakeholders at meetings on agriculture. These have included meetings with the National Farmers’ Union, the Farmers’ Union of Wales, the National Pig Association and attendance at DEFRA’s stakeholder roundtables, one of which focused on farming and horticulture.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-03-13T16:25:52.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707723/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707723/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707723/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-03-03","Agriculture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what recent discussions his Department has had with representatives of the agricultural sector on the implications on agriculture of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","66505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707724","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-13","<p>The Falkland Islands has received funding from the European Commission's voluntary scheme for Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services in Territories of European overseas (BEST) Programme and the European Development Fund (EDF).</p><p>According to the Falkland Islands Government, over the last 5 years, they have received €491,032 of BEST payments and the following EDF payments:</p><ul><li>2012: €0</li><li>2013: €0</li><li>2014: €1,030,000</li><li>2015: €925,000</li><li>2016: €950,000</li></ul>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-03-13T17:57:45.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707724/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707724/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-03","EU Grants and Loans: Falkland Islands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much EU funding the Falkland Islands has received in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Wes Streeting","Ilford North","Wes Streeting","66512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707725","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-03-13","<p>The Department for Exiting the EU has engaged with a range of higher education institutions and groups through visits, meetings and forums. Over the coming weeks and months the department will continue to engage with key stakeholders in business and civil society, including universities, through roundtables, bi-laterals and visits across the UK.</p><p>We have been clear that we want to create an environment in which the UK as a whole can continue to be a world leader in research, science and the tertiary education sector more broadly. The government has announced that UK researchers can still apply for Horizon 2020 projects and the Treasury will underwrite the payment of such awards, even when specific projects continue beyond the UK’s departure from the EU. Equally, existing EU students and those starting courses in 2017/18 will continue to be eligible for student loans and will be for the duration of their course.</p><p>Jo Johnson - Minister for Universities, Science, Research and Innovation – has also set up a forum with a number of senior representatives of UK research and innovation organisations to discuss opportunities and issues arising from the UK’s exit from the European Union. This group will work with Government to ensure it has the best evidence to keep the UK punching above its weight in research and innovation.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-03-13T16:24:57.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707725/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707725/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-03-03","Universities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what steps his Department has taken to engage with UK universities in relation to the negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","66504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707726","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-13","<p>A competitive and transparent financial services sector is vital to ensuring that the UK economy delivers for consumers and businesses.</p><p> </p><p>As with all policy areas, the Government continues to keep transparency of foreign exchange fees under review, and is currently conducting research on the effects of transparency on consumer decisions.</p><p> </p><p>This will help inform the Government’s approach to foreign exchange transactions within the Payment Services Regulations, which are currently being consulted on as part of the transposition of the Second Payment Services Directive.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","66468","2017-03-13T14:14:24.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707726/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707726/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-03","Foreign Exchange","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he plans to include provisions relating to (a) transparency and (b) changes in foreign currency transactions in the Payment Services Regulations 2017.","false","Biography information for Tom Tugendhat","Tonbridge and Malling","Tom Tugendhat","66469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707727","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-13","<p>A competitive and transparent financial services sector is vital to ensuring that the UK economy delivers for consumers and businesses.</p><p> </p><p>As with all policy areas, the Government continues to keep transparency of foreign exchange fees under review, and is currently conducting research on the effects of transparency on consumer decisions.</p><p> </p><p>This will help inform the Government’s approach to foreign exchange transactions within the Payment Services Regulations, which are currently being consulted on as part of the transposition of the Second Payment Services Directive.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","66469","2017-03-13T14:14:24.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707727/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707727/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-03","Foreign Exchange","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress has been made on the Government's plans to increase transparency in foreign currency transactions.","false","Biography information for Tom Tugendhat","Tonbridge and Malling","Tom Tugendhat","66468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707205","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-10","<p>The Government is committed to maximising electoral registration, helping to ensure every voice matters in a democracy that works for everyone. Online registration has made registration easier, simpler and faster and it is more in tune with the digital lives many people now lead – particularly young people. Since the introduction of Individual Electoral Registration, there have been over 1.3 million applications to register to vote made by people aged 16 and 17, with over half of the applications made online.</p><p> </p><p>As part of my 'Every Voice Matters' tour, I have met with a number of sixth form students across the country to hear – first hand – about the barriers they face to engaging in the democratic process. This insight is helping inform a wider democratic engagement strategy, which the Government will publish later in 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The Autumn 2015 Spending Review announced over £1 billion to expand National Citizen Service (NCS) over the next 4 years, meaning that by 2021, NCS will cover 60% of all 16 year olds and it is being expanded to include democratic engagement.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-03-10T14:37:12.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707205/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707205/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707205/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-03-02","Electoral Register: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps his Department is taking to encourage people aged 16 or 17 to register to vote.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","66274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707206","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-09","<p>As part of my Every Voice Matters Tour, I have held roundtable discussions with various organisations that represent people with disabilities to further understand the barriers disabled people face in engaging in the democratic process and to find possible solutions. A number of issues are being considered by the Cabinet Office-chaired Accessibility of Elections Group, which includes representatives from Mencap, Royal National Institute Of Blind People (RNIB), the Association of Electoral Administrators and the Electoral Commission, to support the Government’s commitment to making the electoral system fully accessible for all elections.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-03-09T12:16:55.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707206/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707206/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-03-02","Electoral Register: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps the Government is taking to make registration and voting more accessible to people with disabilities.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","66275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707207","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-09","<p>In its response to Sir Eric Pickles’ review of electoral fraud, the Government announced its intention to run a number of pilot schemes at local government elections in May 2018. The pilot schemes are part of a comprehensive programme of reform that will enhance public confidence in our elections, and strengthen electoral integrity.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is keen to be inclusive in making plans to bring forward Sir Eric’s recommendations. The Government is conscious of the need to ensure that legitimate electors are not disenfranchised, and will give careful consideration to the impacts of the pilots. Over the coming weeks and months, the Government will be working with its key electoral partners, including the Electoral Commission, the Association of Electoral Administrators, and the Society of Local Authority Chief Executives, to set out in detail our plans for implementing and evaluating the pilot schemes.</p><p> </p><p>The pilot schemes will enable us to accurately determine the impact of asking voters in Great Britain to present identification before voting. This, in turn, will ensure that the Government can build a clear, secure democracy that works for everyone.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","66325","2017-03-09T12:20:18.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707207/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707207/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-03-02","Polling Stations: Proof of Identity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the announcement of 27 December 2016, Press release: Eliminating electoral fraud in polling stations, when the Government plans to publish further guidance on the trial of identification in polling stations at the local government elections in May 2018; and whether the Government plans that that guidance will clarify (a) how the Government will communicate those changes to electors and (b) what training will be given to polling station staff.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","66287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707208","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>Information on how much has been spent on central government procurement is set out in the annual reports on SME spend, which can be found at the following links:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/central-government-spend-with-smes-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/central-government-spend-with-smes-2014-to-2015</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/231994/SME_Two_Year_On_Report.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/231994/SME_Two_Year_On_Report.pdf</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/departmental-spending-with-smes" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/departmental-spending-with-smes</a></p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-03-07T11:47:54.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707208/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707208/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-03-02","Government Departments: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much has been spent on central government procurement in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","66291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707209","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>Information on the ownership of companies winning government contracts is not currently held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy has established a register of people with significant control (PSC register). Companies, Societates Europaeae (SEs) and limited liability partnerships (LLPs) will be required to identify and record the people who own or control their company and must file the PSC information with the central public register at Companies House.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-03-07T11:48:39.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707209/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707209/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707209/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-03-02","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many companies owned by tax exiles have been awarded public contracts in each of the last five years for which data is available; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","66293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707210","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-10","<p>As the UK Digital Strategy and<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/government-transformation-strategy-2017-to-2020/government-transformation-strategy" target="_blank"> Government Transformation Strategy</a> both set out, government is committed to building and extending the use of shared components and platforms. GOV.UK Verify is government’s single, shared identity platform for citizens.</p><p> </p><p>The authentication service being developed by HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) to replace Government Gateway will be for business representatives. HMRC is committed to GOV.UK Verify as the government’s identity platform for citizens.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC is the biggest user of GOV.UK Verify, enabling access to its citizen-facing services such as Self Assessment, Personal Tax Accounts and other associated services, such as Check Your Income Tax.</p><p> </p><p>The Government Digital Service is working closely with HMRC and across government to develop a shared migration plan to GOV.UK Verify for citizen-facing services currently using Government Gateway.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-03-10T13:55:32.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707210/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707210/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-03-02","Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the HM Revenue and Customs Digital press release of 13 February 2017, Green light for Government Gateway Transformation, which future transactions will be processed through the (a) new verification service and (b) Government Digital Service platform Verify.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","66306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707211","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-09","<p>The Government provided £14 million across 2013/14 and 2014/15 to support the costs of activities – at a local and national level – to maximise the number of people on the register. £2.5 million of this was allocated to a number of civil society and national organisations, which looked at increasing registration amongst particular groups. This included groups such as Mencap, British Youth Council and Operation Black Vote.</p><p> </p><p>The funding allocated to local authorities was shared across the country, with a formula in place to determine which areas should receive a larger share, based on evidence of under registration in particular areas.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-03-09T12:11:48.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707211/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707211/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-03-02","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the Written Statement of 9 January 2015, HCWS 180, on maximising voter registration, which local authorities and organisations have received funding; how much funding each local authority or organisation received; who has responsibility for monitoring activity locally; and what evaluation processes are in place to assess the effect of that activity on under-registered groups.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","66307"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707212","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-09","<p>In its response to Sir Eric Pickles’ review of electoral fraud, the Government announced its intention to run a number of pilot schemes at local government elections in May 2018. The pilot schemes are part of a comprehensive programme of reform that will enhance public confidence in our elections, and strengthen electoral integrity.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is keen to be inclusive in making plans to bring forward Sir Eric’s recommendations. The Government is conscious of the need to ensure that legitimate electors are not disenfranchised, and will give careful consideration to the impacts of the pilots. Over the coming weeks and months, the Government will be working with its key electoral partners, including the Electoral Commission, the Association of Electoral Administrators, and the Society of Local Authority Chief Executives, to set out in detail our plans for implementing and evaluating the pilot schemes.</p><p> </p><p>The pilot schemes will enable us to accurately determine the impact of asking voters in Great Britain to present identification before voting. This, in turn, will ensure that the Government can build a clear, secure democracy that works for everyone.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","66287","2017-03-09T12:20:18.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707212/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707212/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707212/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-03-02","Electoral Register: Proof of Identity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to his Department's press release of 27 December 2016, Eliminating Electoral Fraud in Polling Stations, if he will carry out an equality and human rights impact assessment on the voter identification pilots; and whether he plans to make an assessment of the effect of those pilots on the demographic composition of voters in future elections.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","66325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707213","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-07","<p>The Government levies no duty on aviation gasoline when used in international flights, consistent with international conventions. When used in other ways aviation gasoline is levied at £0.3770 per litre.</p><p> </p><p>As with all taxes the Government keeps this under review.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-03-07T14:47:48.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707213/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707213/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707213/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-02","Aviation: Fuels","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of reducing the tax on aviation gasoline.","false","Biography information for Sir Roger Gale","North Thanet","Sir Roger Gale","66370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707214","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-10","<p>HM Revenue and Customs are not able to disaggregate statistics on tax accruals down to lower level trade sector such as flight schools.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-03-10T11:39:55.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707214/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707214/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707214/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-02","Aviation: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much (a) income tax and (b) VAT was accrued to the public purse from activities related to flight training schools in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","66376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707215","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-07","<p>The £2.3bn Housing Infrastructure Fund, announced at Autumn Statement, will be used to deliver infrastructure, such as new roads and utility networks, to unlock up to 100,000 homes in high demand areas.</p><p> </p><p>The fund will open to bids from local authorities in the areas of greatest housing need later this year, and will be competitively allocated to ensure that we fund the right infrastructure in the right places. Further detail will be set out by the Department for Communities and Local Government in due course.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-03-07T15:03:26.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707215/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707215/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707215/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-02","Housing Infrastructure Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 29 November 2016 to Question 55287, on Housing Infrastructure Fund, when further details will be sent out regarding that fund including when local authorities will be able to apply for funding; and when funding will be received by those authorities that apply to that fund successfully.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","66396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707216","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-10","<p>Government departments buy copyright licences according to their needs from their departmental budgets. Funds are not allocated by HM Treasury specifically for licensing and departmental procurement. This type of procurement is a matter for individual departments.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-03-10T11:07:29.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707216/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707216/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707216/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-02","Government Departments: Copyright","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what process his Department has for allocating funds for the payment for copyright licenses by the Government; and what funds were allocated for such payments in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Dowd","Lewisham West and Penge","Jim Dowd","66284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707217","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-10","<p>The Government is committed to improving air quality, and will consult on a detailed draft plan later this year which will set out how we will achieve our air quality goals. Alongside this, the Government will continue to explore the appropriate tax treatment for diesel vehicles, and will continue to engage with stakeholders.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","66278","2017-03-10T11:38:08.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707217/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707217/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707217/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-02","Diesel Vehicles: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make it his policy to increase road tax for diesel vehicles.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","66277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707218","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-10","<p>The Government is committed to improving air quality, and will consult on a detailed draft plan later this year which will set out how we will achieve our air quality goals. Alongside this, the Government will continue to explore the appropriate tax treatment for diesel vehicles, and will continue to engage with stakeholders.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","66277","2017-03-10T11:38:08.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707218/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707218/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707218/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-02","Diesel Fuel: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he plans to increase taxes on diesel fuel.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","66278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707219","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-07","<p>A competitive and transparent financial services sector is vital to ensuring that the UK economy delivers for consumers and businesses.</p><p> </p><p>As with all policy areas, the Government continues to keep transparency of foreign exchange fees under review, and is currently conducting research on the effects of this on consumer decisions to inform its policy approach.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is also currently consulting on its draft regulations for the implementation of the Second Payment Services Directive and will respond in due course.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","66413","2017-03-07T10:07:45.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707219/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707219/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707219/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-02","Foreign Exchange","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress the Government has made on bringing greater transparency to foreign currency transactions.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","66412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707220","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-07","<p>A competitive and transparent financial services sector is vital to ensuring that the UK economy delivers for consumers and businesses.</p><p> </p><p>As with all policy areas, the Government continues to keep transparency of foreign exchange fees under review, and is currently conducting research on the effects of this on consumer decisions to inform its policy approach.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is also currently consulting on its draft regulations for the implementation of the Second Payment Services Directive and will respond in due course.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","66412","2017-03-07T10:07:45.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707220/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707220/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707220/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-02","Foreign Exchange","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if the Government will take steps to make currency conversion fully transparent in forthcoming payment services regulations.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","66413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707221","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-09","<p>The Government is committed to preventing homelessness. It is essential that vulnerable people have access to good quality private rented sector accommodation.</p><p>As part of the almost £14 million investment from 2010 to 2016 for the Crisis access to private rented sector accommodation programme, projects in Birmingham received £194, 000 across two projects from 2011-2014. These worked to help young people access the private rented sector and secure sustainable move-on accommodation.</p><p>In addition, through our £50 million Homelessness Prevention Programme, Birmingham will receive £1,700,000 in Trailblazer funding to focus on early interventions. We are also investing £400,000 in Solihull and Birmingham to identify those at risk of rough sleeping, and support them into sustainable accommodation.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-03-09T15:37:56.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707221/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707221/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707221/answer","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707221/answer/previousversion/39074","Biography information for Lord Barwell","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-02","Private Rented Housing: Birmingham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 28 February 2017 to Question 64623, on rented housing, how much funding for help to rent projects the Government has provided to Birmingham City Council in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","66411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707222","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-20","<p>The Government is committed to building a strong and safe private rented sector, which provides security and stability for both tenants and landlords. We announced at the 2016 Autumn Statement a ban on letting agent fees paid by tenants, to improve competition in the private rental market and give renters greater clarity and control over what they will pay. The Government will consult in the Spring on the detail of implementation.</p><p>The Housing White Paper outlines the Government’s intention to promote fairness and transparency for the growing number of leaseholders. We will consult on a range of measures to tackle all unfair and unreasonable abuses of leasehold and consider further reforms through the consultation to improve consumer choice and fairness for leaseholders.</p><p>An increasing number of private tenants are happy with their tenure and standards are improving. We are determined to ensure all sectors of the housing market provide decent homes.</p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-03-20T15:24:59.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707222/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707222/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707222/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-02","Private Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to monitor (a) letting agent fees, (b) lease terms and (c) safety standards in rented properties.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","66288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707223","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-13","<p>The Government will be consulting on a range of measures in the Housing White Paper. On Chapters 3 and 4, these include:</p><ul><li><p>A consultation seeking views on planning measures to support an increase in Build to Rent schemes across England. Further details on the consultation and how to respond can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/planning-and-affordable-housing-for-build-to-rent" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/planning-and-affordable-housing-for-build-to-rent</a></p></li><li><p>A consultation on the definition of affordable housing for planning purposes and amendments to Starter Homes policy. Further details on the consultation and how to respond can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/fixing-our-broken-housing-market-consultation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/fixing-our-broken-housing-market-consultation</a></p></li><li><p>A commitment to consult on banning lettings agents fees to tenants ahead of legislation.</p></li><li><p>A commitment to consult on a range of measures to tackle unfair and unreasonable abuses of leasehold.</p></li><li><p>A commitment to bring forward a Green Paper on implementing the new funding model for Supported Housing and the approach to short term accommodation.</p></li></ul>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-03-13T17:13:52.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707223/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707223/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707223/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-02","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will take steps to consult on Chapters 3 and 4 of his Department's White Paper, entitled Fixing our broken housing market, Cm 9352, published in February 2017.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","66309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707224","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-13","<p>The Northern Powerhouse is fundamental to the Government’s plan for an economy that works for everyone. That is why we announced our strategy to take forward the Northern Powerhouse at Autumn Statement and in January allocated £556 million of investment to the Northern Powerhouse. The economic opportunities that the Northern Powerhouse is creating will benefit everyone in the North, regardless of gender, age or ethnicity.</p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy",,"2017-03-13T17:46:36.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707224/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707224/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-02","Regional Planning and Development: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how he plans to increase economic opportunities for women in the Northern Powerhouse.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","66303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707225","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-07","<p>The Government will examine the options for reforming the system of developer contributions including ensuring direct benefit for communities, and will respond to the independent review and make an announcement at Autumn Budget 2017.</p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-03-07T17:22:17.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707225/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707225/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707225/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-02","Community Infrastructure Levy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the oral contribution of 27 February 2017, Official Report, column 6, whether the Government plans to maintain the level of Community Infrastructure Levy returned to a community at 25 per cent once a Neighbourhood Plan is in place.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","66397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707226","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-16","<p>Rateable values are set independently of ministers by the Valuation Office Agency. The Government has put in place a £3.6 billion package of transitional relief to support those businesses facing an increase. Additionally, my Department has been working closely with the Treasury to determine how best to provide further support to those businesses with the steepest increases.</p><p>A package of support was subsequently announced at the Budget on 8 March. It includes £110 million to support rate-payers losing small business rates relief and rural rate relief as a result of the 2017 revaluation, as well as a £300 million discretionary relief fund for local authorities to help individual businesses that are having the greatest difficulties paying increased rates bills.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-16T14:10:05.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707226/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707226/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-02","Pre-school Education: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effect of business rate revaluations on the financial sustainability of private nursery providers.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","66388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707227","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-07","<p>The effect of the revaluation of business rates on businesses in (a) Camberwell and Peckham and (b) the London Borough of Southwark will depend on the specific circumstances and location of the relevant property. A £3.6 billion transitional relief scheme will provide support to properties which face an increase in rates. My Department is working closely with the Treasury to determine how best to provide further support to businesses facing the steepest increases. We expect to be in a position to make an announcement on this at the Budget.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-07T17:32:01.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707227/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707227/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707227/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-02","Non-domestic Rates: Southwark","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many businesses in (a) Camberwell and Peckham constituency and (b) the London Borough of Southwark will be affected by the 2017 change in rateable values.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","66392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707228","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-20","<p>The Government is supporting home buyers with small deposits to achieve their home ownership aspirations through a number of measures:</p><ul><li>Operating the Help to Buy Equity Loan scheme, which offers a government equity loan of up to 20 per cent (up to 40 per cent in London) of the price of a new build home up to the value of £600,000;</li><li>The Government’s Help to Buy ISA helps to boost the savings of prospective first-time buyers. It offers a 25 per cent savings bonus, up to a maximum of £3,000, towards the purchase of a first home;</li><li>In April 2017, the Government will also introduce the Lifetime ISA. This will support younger adults to save flexibly for the long term, giving them a 25 per cent bonus on up to £4,000 of savings a year. Savings and the bonus can be put towards the purchase of a first home, or withdrawn once they reach the age of 60.</li><li>Shared Ownership enables people to buy a share of a new home built with a public grant provided for developing that home. Purchasers are able to buy a share of between 25 per cent and 75 per cent (depending on what they can afford and what is available) and pay a subsidised rent on the remainder. Purchasers are able to buy further shares in their homes in minimum 10 per cent instalments.</li></ul><p>More details on support from the Government towards home –buyers with small deposits can be found between pages 58-61 of the recently published Housing White Paper (February 2017):</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/590464/Fixing_our_broken_housing_market_-_print_ready_version.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/590464/Fixing_our_broken_housing_market_-_print_ready_version.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-03-20T15:26:54.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707228/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707228/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707228/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-02","First Time Buyers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what plans the Government has to support home-buyers with small deposits.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","66377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707229","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-10","<p>We intend to issue a consultation on making company directors accountable for breaches of the Privacy and Electronic Communications Regulations 2003 in in due course.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-10T11:35:28.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707229/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707229/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707229/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-02","Direct Marketing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when she plans to launch the consultation on making company directors and those in similar positions accountable for breaches of the Privacy and Electronic Communications Regulations 2003 in relation to direct marketing; and what the period of that consultation will be.","false","Biography information for Patricia Gibson","North Ayrshire and Arran","Patricia Gibson","66379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707230","Department for Education","false","2017-03-07","<p>Ada National College for Digital Skills opened to its first cohort of students in September 2016. 58 students have been enrolled at the College in the current year, of which 11 percent are from outside Greater London. The College has received 177 applications for the autumn 2017 intake. Over 20 percent of these applicants are from outside Greater London.</p><p> </p><p>The College is talking to industry partners about a range of options for growth outside London by 2020; and is planning to launch an online training pilot in advanced digital skills in Summer 2017.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-03-07T16:41:08.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707230/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707230/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707230/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-02","Ada, National College for Digital Skills","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of how many National College for Digital Skills students in the (a) current and (b) next cohort are resident outside London.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","66375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707231","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-07","<p>Yes, the Government's continued commitment to this policy was outlined in the Digital Strategy launched last week on the 1st of March 2017.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-07T11:22:47.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707231/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707231/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707231/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-02","Digital Technology: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to page 41 of the Government's industrial strategy green paper, published in January 2017, whether it remains her Department's policy that free basic digital skills training will be available for all adults.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","66371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707232","Department for Education","false","2017-03-07","<p>The Government intends to consult with sector experts, education providers and the public to ensure that adults who lack core digital skills can access specified basic digital skills training. We will also work closely with key stakeholders in order to identify, and where required, support the quality improvement of the most appropriate courses and qualifications for these adults to ensure they can secure basic digital skills.</p><p> </p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-03-07T09:33:16.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707232/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707232/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707232/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-02","Digital Technology: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to page 5, Part 2 of the Government's Digital Strategy, published on 1 March 2017, with whom she plans to consult to ensure that adults who lack core digital skills can access specified basic digital skills training; and what qualifications she envisages those adults attaining on completion of that training.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","66385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707233","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-07","<p>The UK’s negotiations for exiting the EU are complex and the Government is focused on securing the best deal for Britain. Together with the Department for Exiting the EU, we are analysing all the impacts of leaving the EU, looking at over 50 sectors. Once we have left the EU, decisions on how taxpayers’ money will be spent will be made in the UK. There may be European programmes in which we might want to participate, but this will be a decision for the UK as we negotiate the new arrangements.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","66356","2017-03-07T11:24:34.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707233/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707233/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707233/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-02","Culture: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the UK's potential relationship with Creative Europe after (a) the UK leaves the EU and (b) Creative Europe's current budget period ends in 2020.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","66355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707234","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-07","<p>The UK’s negotiations for exiting the EU are complex and the Government is focused on securing the best deal for Britain. Together with the Department for Exiting the EU, we are analysing all the impacts of leaving the EU, looking at over 50 sectors. Once we have left the EU, decisions on how taxpayers’ money will be spent will be made in the UK. There may be European programmes in which we might want to participate, but this will be a decision for the UK as we negotiate the new arrangements.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","66355","2017-03-07T11:24:34.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707234/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707234/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707234/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-02","Culture: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the potential benefits to the audiovisual, creative and cultural sectors of continued participation in Creative Europe and its successors after the UK leaves the EU; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","66356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707235","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-08","<p>I expect to announce the Chair of the independent review of full-time social action by young people in due course. Following the appointment of the Chair we will appoint a panel of experts from the private and voluntary sectors.</p><p><br> Officials in my department are providing the secretariat for the review including preliminary work in advance of the Chair and panel appointments.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2017-03-08T12:10:05.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707235/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707235/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707235/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-02","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what progress her Department has made on its independent review of full-time volunteering by young people.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","66308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707236","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-07","<p>Public libraries play a significant role in providing people with access to the internet and digital services, through computers, wifi and other digital technologies, as well as offering digital skills training and support to local people. A number of funding opportunities are available to public libraries in England to support them in providing improved services.</p><p> </p><p>These include a £4m public libraries innovation fund that was launched in December 2016 and managed by Arts Council England on behalf of DCMS. This fund will support a range of innovative library service projects in 2017/18 to benefit disadvantaged people and places in England and could include access to technology provided by library services. This is in addition to the Government funding programme, managed by Arts Council England, that supported the roll out of wifi in 2015/16 so that almost every public library in England now provides free wifi to the public.</p><p> </p><p>DCMS is also providing funding and support to library authorities interested in developing alternative delivery models including mutuals which could help them be more flexible in responding to the needs of their local communities, such as providing digital access, training and support.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2017-03-07T12:32:40.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707236/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707236/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707236/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-02","Public Libraries: Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to Part 2 of the Government's UK Digital Strategy, published on 1 March 2017, whether additional funding will be provided to libraries to help make them the go-to provider of digital access, training and support for local communities.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","66418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707237","Department for Education","false","2017-03-07","<p>The government is committing to ensuring that, where relevant learners get a place to study for a relevant digital skills qualification, it will be free of charge. This support is available for adults aged 19+ in England who are considered to lack basic digital skills. Funding will be via the £1.5 billion Adult Education Budget. This is currently allocated to providers who decide on actual provision according to the local labour market and learner demand and so levels of funding will vary from year to year but will be delivered within the limits of the budget of each provider.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-03-07T09:32:56.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707237/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707237/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707237/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-02","Digital Technology: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to page 5, Part 2 of the Government's Digital Strategy, published on 1 March 2017, whether additional funding will be provided to ensure that adults who lack core digital skills can access specified basic digital skills training free of charge.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","66416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707238","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-07","<p>There are 11 members of the Royal Navy Police working on Iraq Historic Allegations Team (IHAT) investigations. IHAT investigations are conducted under the statutory framework of the Armed Forces Act 2006, and while members of the Royal Navy Police attached to IHAT carry out a range of duties they have the particular role of exercising functions which under the Act can only be exercised by Service Police.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-03-07T15:13:10.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707238/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707238/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707238/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-02","Iraq Historic Allegations Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many members of the Royal Navy Police are working as part of the Iraq Historic Allegations Team; and what duties those members have.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","66422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707239","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-07","<p>As at 3 March 2017, the Order of Battle for the Royal Navy Police is:</p><p> </p><p>Provost Marshal Navy Headquarters</p><p> </p><p>Naval Provost Marshal Eastern Region</p><p> </p><p>Naval Provost Marshal Western Region</p><p> </p><p>Naval Provost Marshal Northern Region</p><p> </p><p>Royal Navy Special Investigation Branch Eastern Region</p><p> </p><p>Royal Navy Special Investigation Branch Western Region</p><p> </p><p>There are discreet numbers of Royal Navy Police that are employed in policing and non-policing roles across Defence.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-03-07T15:09:24.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707239/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707239/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707239/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-02","Royal Navy Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the Order of Battle of the Royal Navy Police is.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","66423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707240","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-07","<p>The Royal Navy Police and Royal Military Police do not have military working dogs. The Royal Air Force Police currently have 203 dogs and they are employed in roles such as general purpose policing, protection, vehicle search, arms explosive search, drugs detection, patrol, and explosive detection.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-03-07T15:11:51.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707240/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707240/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707240/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-02","Armed Forces: Dogs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many military working dogs are in service in the (a) Royal Navy Police, (b) Royal Military Police and (c) Royal Air Force Police; and what duties those dogs perform in each such service.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","66398"
